    "narrative": "Our strongest plays for today\u2019s slate are anchored by **Cal Raleigh** (71.30) and **Will Smith** (70.62). **Cal Raleigh** draws a favorable matchup against Liberatore; his score is significantly elevated by his #2 spot in the order and the favorable platoon advantage. **Will Smith** is similarly positioned, benefiting from a soft matchup against Colin Rea and projected wind conditions that could turn a marginal park factor into a genuine power threat. In the middle infield, **Geraldo Perdomo** (68.05) remains our primary engine for the scarce stolen base category; despite the volatility of the #1 spot, his matchup against the soft-tossing Germ\u00e1n M\u00e1rquez gives him an elite SP skill boost that makes him a lock for our lineup.\n\nWe are navigating a few high-stakes pivot points. **Taylor Ward** (59.46) is a classic \"start despite the matchup\" candidate; while he faces an elite arm in Crochet, the massive park-factor boost (16%) keeps him firmly in our starting nine. Conversely, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (59.41) faces a tough road against Gausman, and his BvP struggles over 26 plate appearances have tempered his floor. The most difficult bench decision involved **Gleyber Torres** (50.43), who sits just outside the threshold for entry; despite his decent raw projection, his platoon disadvantage against Singer and the optimizer\u2019s preference for higher-efficiency slots pushed him to the bench. We must also monitor the status of **Bryson Stott**, **Geraldo Perdomo**, **Will Smith**, **Gavin Sheets**, and **Wenceel Perez**, all of whom are currently projected based on assumed lineup spots. Should any of them move down the order or be held out, their efficiency scores will collapse, and we will need to pivot to the high-floor but low-ceiling alternatives on our bench, such as **Yainer Diaz**.",
